# Hermes secrets — COPY to `secrets.env` (same dir), fill in, chmod 0600.
#   cp secrets.env.example secrets.env && chmod 600 secrets.env && $EDITOR secrets.env
#
# `secrets.env` is git-ignored (see ./.gitignore). deploy.sh reads it and
# renders ~hermes/.hermes/.env (0600), which Hermes loads at runtime.
# Preflight refuses to deploy if the REQUIRED values below are missing.
# Use a DEDICATED bot token + a DEDICATED, low-limit LLM key here, so a leak via
# the agent (prompt injection can read this file) is cheap to rotate and scoped.

# === Discord (REQUIRED) ==================================================
# Bot token from the Discord Developer Portal. Enable the privileged intents
# "Message Content" and "Server Members" on the bot, or it won't read messages.
DISCORD_BOT_TOKEN=

# Allowlist — REQUIRED and must be NON-EMPTY (deploy refuses an open bot).
# Comma-separated Discord user IDs allowed to talk to the agent.
DISCORD_ALLOWED_USERS=
# Optional: comma-separated role IDs (in addition to / instead of users).
#DISCORD_ALLOWED_ROLES=

# === LLM provider — set EXACTLY ONE key (remote API) =====================
# Match the key to LLM_PROVIDER in config.sh (default provider: openrouter).
OPENROUTER_API_KEY=
#ANTHROPIC_API_KEY=
#OPENAI_API_KEY=
#GROQ_API_KEY=

# === Optional: loopback API (only if PUBLISH_API=1 in config.sh) =========
# Hermes's OpenAI-compatible API needs a key (>= 8 chars). Bound to 127.0.0.1.
#API_SERVER_KEY=

# -------------------------------------------------------------------------
# DO NOT set the following — deploy.sh hard-locks them for safety, and setting
# them here would weaken the sandbox:
#   TERMINAL_ENV            (forced to `local` — the container is the jail)
#   GATEWAY_ALLOW_ALL_USERS (forced to `false`)
#   SUDO_PASSWORD           (plaintext sudo escalation — never)
#   HERMES_DOCKER_BINARY / TERMINAL_DOCKER_* / TERMINAL_SSH_* (other backends)
